      "content_html": "<a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/07/18/portsmouth-sinfonia.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"An orchestra with inept players sold out the Royal Albert Hall\"><img alt=\"Portsmouth Sinfonia — Diliff / CC BY-SA 3.0 (Wikimedia Commons)\" class=\"webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image\" height=\"651\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/1280px-Royal_Albert_Hall2C_London_-_Nov_2012.jpg?fit=1280%2C651&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto; margin-bottom: 5px;\" width=\"1280\" /></a><p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">In 1970, composer Gavin Bryars and a group of students at the Portsmouth School of Art formed the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portsmouth_Sinfonia\">Portsmouth Sinfonia</a>, an orchestra open to anyone regardless of talent. Trained musicians could join too, as long as they picked an instrument entirely new to them. &#8212; <a class=\"read-more\" href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/07/18/portsmouth-sinfonia.html\">Read the rest </a></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/07/18/portsmouth-sinfonia.html\">An orchestra with inept players sold out the Royal Albert Hall</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://boingboing.net\">Boing Boing</a>.</p>",
